          <div class="learn__post__content">
            <p>
              Collections keep questions, dashboards, and models organized and
              easy to find. Its helpful to think of collections as folders that
              store our work. Collection permissions give <a
                href="/learn/metabase-basics/administration/permissions/strategy#how-to-approach-permissions"
                >groups of people</a
              > access to:
            </p>

            <ul>
              <li>
                View or edit the questions, dashboards, or models saved in a
                collection.
              </li>
              <li>
                Edit collection details, such as a collections name, or where
                its saved.
              </li>
            </ul>

            <p>
              In this tutorial, well create collections for a company with
              teams called Canoes and Sailboats, and set up collection
              permissions so that:
            </p>

            <ul>
              <li>
                Everyone at the company can view, but not edit, the work thats
                saved in the top-level collection for the company (in Metabase,
                its called <strong>Our analytics</strong>you might think of
                this as a root directory or a parent folder).
              </li>
              <li>
                People on the Canoes team will be able to save, view, and edit
                work thats shared between team members in the Canoes
                collection. People on the Sailboats team will get access to
                their own Sailboats collection.
              </li>
              <li>
                The Canoes team will get view-only access to the work saved in
                the Sailboats collection. The Sailboats team will get view-only
                access to the Canoes collection.
              </li>
            </ul>

            <h2 id="reviewing-the-default-collection-permissions">
              Reviewing the default collection permissions
            </h2>

            <p>In a fresh, brand new Metabase:</p>

            <ol>
              <li>
                Click on the <strong>gear icon</strong> and select <strong
                  >Admin settings</strong
                > &gt; <strong>Permissions</strong> &gt; <strong
                  >Collections</strong
                >.
              </li>
              <li>
                Click on <strong>Our analytics</strong> to go to the collection permissions
                page for the root collection.
              </li>
            </ol>

            <p>
              From the <strong>Permissions for Our analytics</strong> page, youll
              find that <strong>Collection access</strong> is set to <strong
                >Curate</strong
              > for the default groups Administrators and All Users.
            </p>

            <p>
              All Users includes everyone thats added to your Metabase, and the <strong
                >Curate</strong
              > permission allows a group to view and edit a collection. So, Metabases
              default collection permissions will allow everyone at Boats to view
              and edit the work thats saved in <strong>Our analytics</strong>.
            </p>

            <h2 id="configuring-permissions-to-our-analytics">
              Configuring permissions to Our analytics
            </h2>

            <p>
              Were going to revoke access to <strong>Our analytics</strong>,
              because Metabase grants the <em>most permissive</em> level of access
              across all of the groups that someone belongs to.
            </p>

            <p>
              You cant remove people from the All Users group, so if you give
              All Users <strong>Curate</strong> permissions to <strong
                >Our analytics</strong
              >, then thatll always be the most permissive setting for everyone
              who uses your Metabase, regardless of any other group that you put
              people in.
            </p>

            <ol>
              <li>
                Go to <strong>Admin settings</strong> &gt; <strong
                  >Permissions</strong
                > &gt; <strong>Collections</strong> &gt; <strong
                  >Our analytics</strong
                >.
              </li>
              <li>
                Click on the dropdown menu at the <strong>All Users</strong> row
                and <strong>Collection access</strong> column..
              </li>
              <li>
                Select <strong>No access</strong>. Toggle on <strong
                  >Also change sub-collections</strong
                > so that these permissions apply to all sub-collections nested under
                <strong>Our analytics</strong>.
              </li>
            </ol>

            <p>
              <img
                src="/learn/images/guide-to-collection-permissions/no-access-our-analytics.png"
                alt="Revoking All Users access to the Our analytics collection and its sub-collections."
              />
            </p>

            <h2 id="creating-new-groups-and-collections">
              Creating new groups and collections
            </h2>

            <p>
              Next, well create groups to match our Canoes and Sailboats teams.
              Go to <strong>Admin settings</strong> &gt; <strong>People</strong>
              &gt; <strong>Groups</strong> &gt; <a
                href="/docs/latest/people-and-groups/managing#groups"
                >Create a group</a
              >, and call the group Canoes.
            </p>

            <p>
              To create a new collection, well go to the Metabase homepage and
              click <strong>+ New</strong> &gt; <strong>Collection</strong>.
              Well create two collections named <a
                href="/learn/metabase-basics/administration/permissions/strategy#org-chart-based-permissions"
                >after our new groups</a
              >, and save each of those collections inside <strong
                >Our analytics</strong
              >.
            </p>

            <h2 id="setting-collection-permissions">
              Setting collection permissions
            </h2>

            <p>
              Well set up collection permissions for the Canoes collection
              first, so that:
            </p>

            <ul>
              <li>
                The Canoes group can view and edit questions, dashboards, and
                models saved in the Canoes collection.
              </li>
              <li>
                The Canoes group can move, re-name, or archive the Canoes
                collection.
              </li>
              <li>
                The Sailboats group can only view the work thats saved in the
                Canoes collection.
              </li>
            </ul>

            <p>
              You can navigate back to <strong>Admin settings</strong> and go to
              the collection permissions page for each collection, or you can set
              up permissions directly from the Metabase homepage.
            </p>

            <ol>
              <li>Click on the Canoes collection in the sidebar.</li>
              <li>
                Click on the <strong>lock icon</strong> to open a collection permissions
                modal.
              </li>
              <li>
                Select <strong>Curate</strong> from the dropdown menu for the <strong
                  >Canoes</strong
                > row and <strong>Collection access</strong> column.
              </li>
              <li>
                Select <strong>View</strong> from the dropdown menu for the <strong
                  >Sailboats</strong
                > row and <strong>Collection access</strong> column.
              </li>
              <li>Click <strong>Save</strong>.</li>
            </ol>

            <p>
              <img
                src="/learn/images/guide-to-collection-permissions/collection-permissions-modal.png"
                alt="Granting different permissions to the Canoes collection."
              />
            </p>

            <p>
              To set up permissions for the <strong>Sailboats</strong> collection
              so that the Sailboats group has <strong>Curate</strong> access, but
              the Canoes group has view-only access:
            </p>

            <ol>
              <li>
                Click on the <strong>Sailboats</strong> collection in the sidebar.
              </li>
              <li>
                Click on the <strong>lock icon</strong> to open a collection permissions
                modal.
              </li>
              <li>
                Select <strong>Curate</strong> from the dropdown menu for the <strong
                  >Sailboats</strong
                > row and <strong>Collection access</strong> column.
              </li>
              <li>
                Select <strong>View</strong> from the dropdown menu for the <strong
                  >Canoes</strong
                > row and <strong>Collection access</strong> column.
              </li>
              <li>Click <strong>Save</strong>.</li>
            </ol>

            <h2 id="how-collection-permissions-interact-with-data-permissions">
              How collection permissions interact with data permissions
            </h2>

            <table>
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Collection permissions</th>
                  <th
                    ><a
                      href="/learn/metabase-basics/administration/permissions/data-permissions"
                      >Data permissions</a
                    ></th
                  >
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td data-label="Collection permissions"
                    >View the <em>results</em> of a question, dashboard, or model
                    saved in a given collection.</td
                  >
                  <td data-label="Data permissions"
                    ><em>View and query</em> the underlying tables used by a question,
                    dashboard, or model.</td
                  >
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>

            <p>Lets say that our Canoes group has two sets of permissions:</p>

            <ul>
              <li>
                <strong>Curate</strong> collection permissions to the Canoes collection;
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Can view</strong> data permissions on the <code
                  class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Orders</code
                > table;
              </li>
            </ul>

            <p>
              If the Canoes collection contains a question created using the <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Orders</code
              > table, heres what you can expect each permission to allow the Canoes
              group to do:
            </p>

            <table>
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th><strong>Curate</strong> the Canoes collection</th>
                  <th
                    ><strong>Can view</strong> permissions to <code
                      class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Orders</code
                    ></th
                  >
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td data-label="Curate the Canoes collection"
                    >Edit the question title or description.</td
                  >
                  <td data-label="Can view permissions to Orders"
                    >View the visualization (the result) of the question.</td
                  >
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td data-label="Curate the Canoes collection"
                    >Move or copy the question to another collection.</td
                  >
                  <td data-label="Can view permissions to Orders"
                    >Change the visualization type of the existing result
                    returned by the question.</td
                  >
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>

            <p>
              Essentially, the Canoes group will have the ability to interact
              with the question thats saved in their collection, but they wont
              be able to query any additional data from the <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Orders</code
              > table (whether through the question or the data browser).
            </p>

            <p>
              <img
                src="/learn/images/guide-to-collection-permissions/no-data-access.png"
                alt="Viewing a question saved in an accessible collection with No self-service permissions to the question"
              />
            </p>

            <p>
              To allow people to create and edit questions, you can set the
              Canoes groups <strong>Create query</strong> permissions to <strong
                >Query builder only</strong
              > for the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                >Orders</code
              > table. Then Canoes will be able to:
            </p>

            <ul>
              <li>
                Use the query builder to change the query used by the question.
              </li>
              <li>
                Filter or summarize data from the <code
                  class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Orders</code
                > table to update the result returned by the question.
              </li>
              <li>
                View the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                  >Orders</code
                > table from the link below the question name.
              </li>
            </ul>

            <p>
              <img
                src="/learn/images/guide-to-collection-permissions/full-data-access.png"
                alt="Viewing a question saved in an accessible collection with Unrestricted permissions to the question"
              />
            </p>

            <h2
              id="how-permissions-apply-to-dashboards-with-questions-from-different-collections"
            >
              How permissions apply to dashboards with questions from different
              collections
            </h2>

            <p>
              Lets say that the Canoes group has an updated set of permissions:
            </p>

            <ul>
              <li>
                <strong>Curate</strong> collection permissions to the Canoes collection.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>No access</strong> collection permissions to the Sailboats
                collection.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Can view</strong> data permissions to the <code
                  class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Orders</code
                > table.
              </li>
            </ul>

            <p>
              If all of the questions on a dashboard are also saved in the
              Canoes collection, the Canoes group will see all of the cards:
            </p>

            <p>
              <img
                src="/learn/images/guide-to-collection-permissions/full-dash-card-access.png"
                alt="Viewing a dashboard with questions saved in an accessible collection."
              />
            </p>

            <p>
              If one of the questions on a dashboard is saved in the Sailboats
              collection (even if that question uses the <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Orders</code
              > table), the Canoes group will see a locked card:
            </p>

            <p>
              <img
                src="/learn/images/guide-to-collection-permissions/partial-dash-card-access.png"
                alt="Viewing a dashboard with a locked card caused by a question saved in an inaccessible collection."
              />
            </p>

            <p>
              Since non-admins arent aware of groups or permissions, locked
              cards can happen when people with broader permissions try to share
              their work with people who have more restricted permissions.
            </p>

            <p>
              For example, lets say that the Pirate Ships group has permissions
              to help themselves from both of the Canoes and Sailboats
              collections. If the Pirate Ships group builds a dashboard and
              shares it with a Canoes group member, the Canoes group member will
              see locked cards for any questions that are still saved in the
              Sailboats collection.
            </p>

            <p>
              To avoid locked cards, we recommend duplicating questions into the
              collection where you intend to save your dashboard.
            </p>

